There is no need to trouble about Virgil's chrono— logy. His Clausus is not the Clausus of Livy, ii. 16, who migrated to Rome in 502 B.C., and founded the gens and tribus Claudia, but an idealised epony- mous ancestor of these, “ belonging to an age anterior to the Romans: which indisputably agrees with the spirit of the early ages” (Niebuhr, “ History of Rome,'' vol. i.‚ p. 560). In lines 708-709, Virgil seems to confuse the original amalgamation of Palatine and Quirinal settlements with the immigration of Clausus: but for his purposes this is of no consequence.

The region to which he now transports us, the Abruzzi of modern Italy, affords another variation on his theme, and a good contrast with the last group of warriors. The towns here are few and small, Amiternum, Nomentum, Eretum, Nursia: there is no great centre like Falerii. We are here almost in the backbone of Italy, and hear the names of rivers and mountains rather than of towns3 and the fighting men are on foot‚ as we should expect of mountaineers.
